the 1100s or so.   Rome of course spent much of its history as a Republic.  And was still called a republic for about 200 years after it became an empire.  My guess is it would have evolved back into a republic.  Much as nucleon had said.  Probably it would still have a ruling figurehead.  Elected consoles and an elected Senate would probably do most of the actual governing.  The plebs, much like in ancient Rome (and as was intended in the House of Reps here) would probably still have their own house.  And Roman democracy would probably look a lot like American democracy (indeed our similarities to Rome is one thing that makes me so interested in Rome).  <br>
<br>
Rome got a bad rap.  They were an incredibly tolerant society.  Their tolerance was a way in which they were like us.  Its survival, as it was in its Imperial heyday, would have been an unparalleled good for the human race.<br>
 <p>&lt;b&gt; &lt;center&gt; Saudi Arabia Delenda Est.&lt;/b&gt;  &lt;/center&gt; </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2894<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/03 3:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> I sometimes wonder if human society hasn't ever advanced beyond our own. We've had eleven ice ages straight that I know about. They last a very long time and each warm interglacial spell is like the World starting over. It's incredible how swiftly farming and civilisation appeared once things warmed up a little. Almost immediately. Perhaps in earlier shortlived heatwaves like this one we actually reached higher degrees of learning than the present, but lost it all when the ice returned. It's a possibility.<br>
The Neanderthal might have been survivors of an earlier warmer age with advanced civilisation and technology beyond our own. I think the last heat spell ended around 40 thousand years ago and the present one began 12 thousand years ago. That's when Cro-magnon stepped in and took over. This interglacial is about finished in fact. We have been in an ice age for millions of years and the cycle is still continuing. When the glaciers recede and the next heat wave warms the Earth there will be almost no trace of our high technology civilisations. Metal rusts, concrete powders away, glass shatters and even plastic dissolves over tens of millenia. Anything that does endure will likely be buried deep and well hidden. Over such endless eons the dim memory of our golden age will likely be forgotten. Rome, Egypt and Babylon were mighty Empires but then the bigger you are the harder you fall. Global civilisations would fall the hardest.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A> at: 1/16/03 3:23:49 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 57<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/03 12:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> We can be pretty sure they did not discover fission at least.  If they did, we would have trace elements of stuff all over with no mechanism to explain it.  While its possible, they probably never developed our modern atomic theory. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 724<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/17/03 9:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> After reading &quot;The Case for Mars,&quot; Zubrin asked a question that stuck in my mind, what if we're doomed to be like a peasant in the Dark Ages who looked upon the Roman aquifers in amazement and wondered how they did it?  I don't think we'll slide so far backwards but I think we could be in for another Dark Age of sorts in that there's a growing desire in people to put the brakes on technological and scientific achievement because they see the future of tech as a displacer of humanity and/or a destroyer of nature.  To change gears somewhat, I remember reading that ancient Romans had developed a miniature steam engine as a toy.  Imagine if they had forseen the power and promise of steam power.  I'm really surprised it took so long for steam power to catch on big. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 1/17/03 9:24:54 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/17/03 11:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> It's amazing how much the ancients really knew.  Hero's engine based on steam was centuries before the Roman Empire.  We have some evidence the Greeks were even inventing Calculus.  We know they knew the world is round.  They had a crude atomic theory.  Some philosophers (namely Anaximander) even speculated the stars were buring balls of flame.<br>
<br>
Too bad people revered Aristotle (who endorsed Ptolemy) as some infallible god of knowledge for so long.  I don't blame him for being wrong.  However, his acolytes should have known better.<br>
<br>
Anway, ever read the Foundation series by Asimov?  It talks about a futuristic dark age.  A bit outdated, but still good works nonetheless. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jkennyu>jkennyu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/21/03 12:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> My understanding is (and Encyclopedia Britanica’s 2001 CD edition..says this also) that the Romans did not just use the steam engine as a toy. They used it as a tool to pump water.  Apparently, it was mainly used to fight fires, but only in a few cities.  For some reason, the idea never caught on more broadly.  I am always amazed at how the ancients were so advanced in many ways.  Hero’s list of inventions is in itself staggering.  Still a number of very practical inventions seem to have eluded the Romans.<br>
<br>
To start with, the Romans should have had everything they needed for a balloon flight.  They had a canvas, designed to keep heat in.  They had baskets, fire, an understanding that fire could make light objects rise. And certainly its military commanders would have felt a burning need to be able to see from higher ground than the opposing commanders could, whatever was happening in the field.  Still, so far as we know, it never happened.  <br>
<br>
A heliograph system should have been easy for the Romans.  They had codes, organization…everything they should have needed to set up a series of heliograph towers, that could have sent messages across the empire in a day.  As opposed to the weeks, it took messages by horse carrier.  Still it never happened.   <br>
<br>
Ahh the foundation series was a masterpiece.  Well the first 3 books were anyway.  Foundation, Foundation and Empire, and Second Foundation.  For some reason, Asimov did all his very best writing as a youth.  Something happened when he went back in his old age to attempt to write more foundation stuff.  It was all pretty dreadful.  I wish he had just left it as the trilogy.  <br>
 <p>&lt;b&gt; &lt;center&gt; Saudi Arabia Delenda Est.&lt;/b&gt;  &lt;/center&gt; </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=foadi@nuclearspace>foadi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/28/03 3:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the world</span><hr size=1> Here's a good article on what could have been had the Roman Empire never collapsed, or perhaps this is where human society could have been had Rome never become an oppressive welfare state:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.lewrockwell.com/orig2/wallace5.html">www.lewrockwell.com/orig2/wallace5.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=contraconstantius>contraconstantius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 6:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> If I remember correctly assassination was accepted by the Romans as fair. Who knows what that could have led to? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 232<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/30/03 6:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A heliograph system should have been easy for the Romans. They had codes, organization…everything they should have needed to set up a series of heliograph towers, that could have sent messages across the empire in a day. As opposed to the weeks, it took messages by horse carrier. Still it never happened. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Probably because it would have been expensive to maintain. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/31/03 11:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> The Romans did actually use optical telegraph systems all along the limes of the empire.  This is what allowed them to control their borders effectively with spaced-out military units (the legions).  I believe that they used flags, smoke signals, and mirrors or lenses in different times and places.  Such systems were very expensive because they were governed the distance at which the human eye can differentiate between different signals, which was not very far.  This required a great many stations and personnel.  No subsequent European state had the economic resources until the 18th century, when people realized that they could use telescopes for observing, thus facilitating a cheaper system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 3:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> I think we should consider that the Roman Empire not collapsing could have been a great setback for civilization.<br>
<br>
It has already been noted that such inventions as the balloon, steam power and effective telegraphy were either overlooked or regarded as mere curiosities by the Romans.  To this list many more can be added.<br>
<br>
There is no guarantee that the Romans would not have simply entered the same kind of introverted, self-obsessed stagnation that China has practiced so successfully for the past several thousand years, ending only in the middle of the last century.<br>
<br>
China has had the time and the resources to conquer the Earth, and indeed the entire solar system if they had progressed faster, for thousands of years, yet they have done nothing but get smacked around like the west's little bitch.<br>
<br>
The birth of modern western civilization lies in the Renaissance, which occurred in the unique social and political environment of middle ages Italy, it is doubtful that, this could have occurred at any other time and place.<br>
<br>
The gifts of the renaissance are the scientific method, reason, self-examination, a strong emphasis on independence and liberty and an almost relentless curiosity and thirst for progress.<br>
<br>
Despite the fact that the fall of the Roman Empire set back technology and civilization 1000 years, and then let us languish in darkness for another 1000, I find it hard to belive that the stodgy and complacent Romans could have come as far in last 1500 years, as we have in the last 500, even with their head start.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 11:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> There may be a fair bit of truth in this, although it is difficult to quantify.  There are a number of theories suggesting that most technological and cultural development comes as a result of competition, not only military but economic, political and ideologicall competition between different regions.  Victor Davis Hanson, for instance, has written a controversial book entitled Carnage and Culture which argues among other things that western societies have maintained a technological, and therefore military, edge throughout history because in the long run they have not settled into a static imperial system.  One needn't agree with many of Hanson's points, certain facets of the argument are quite interesting. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1038<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 1:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> I've often tried to imagine what society would be like right now if the founding fathers had tried to implement strict state socialism where there is no capitalism or any other type of real competition to fuel quick technological advance.  I'm sure they would have tried to stay up militarily with the rest of the world the way the Soviet Union did with the USA, but the USA would have probably fell way short in other places where free markets typically do better such as developing medical and consumer related technology.  I bet we'd be a good hundred years behind where we are now in that type of scenario.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 2/27/03 1:38:15 am<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showPrevMessage?topicID=8.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showNextMessage?topicID=8.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=18><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.emailToFriend?topicID=8.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.threadControl?topicID=8.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/space/deleteThread.gif border=